omplaint about treatment costs","A complaint regarding poor communication","A complaint made without reasonable grounds and intended to harass"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplaint made without reasonable grounds and intended to harass\u003C/strong\u003E is the definition of a vexatious complaint. These complaints are characterised by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPersistent repetition of complaints despite previous investigations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EShifting or evolving allegations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDemands that are disproportionate to the issues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERefusal to accept investigation findings\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHostile or abusive behaviour towards staff\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options describe legitimate complaints:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA complaint about a medical error causing harm\u003C/strong\u003E represents a valid patient safety concern that requires thorough investigation and response.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA complaint regarding poor communication\u003C/strong\u003E highlights legitimate issues in the delivery of patient-centred care that need addressing.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA complaint about waiting times\u003C/strong\u003E raises valid concerns about healthcare accessibility and resource allocation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA complaint about treatment costs\u003C/strong\u003E addresses legitimate concerns regarding healthcare affordability and financial barriers to care.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile healthcare providers have a duty to investigate all complaints initially, they also have the right to protection from vexatious complaints that consume resources without merit.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A vexatious complaint is one that is made without merit, primarily to harass, annoy, or cause distress to the recipient.","Healthcare providers have a legal right to protection from vexatious complaints while maintaining their duty of care.","Identifying features of vexatious complaints include persistent repetition, shifting allegations, and disproportionate demands."],"references":["Vexatious notifications. Agora. https://www.ahpra.gov.au/Notifications/How-we-manage-concerns/Vexatious-notifications.aspx","Mandal J, Ponnambath DK, Parija SC. Bioethics: A brief review. Trop Parasitol. 2017;7(1):5-7. doi:10.4103/tp.TP_4_17","Varkey B. Principles of Clinical Ethics and Their Application to Practice. Med Princ Pract. 2021;30(1):17-28. doi:10.1159/000509119"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58706"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58706"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T09:36:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T09:36:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10547"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73235"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links"